Manageable, but yes,
you already feel it.

00:17:11.029 --> 00:17:15.342
If you wait until launch,

00:17:15.792 --> 00:17:18.712
suddenly you're at €50 or more,

00:17:18.713 --> 00:17:20.204
and that's dinner with wine,

00:17:20.205 --> 00:17:23.875
I would say, and at that point,
the bill really hurts.

00:17:25.043 --> 00:17:26.778
The rule is simple.

00:17:26.945 --> 00:17:29.380
The longer you wait,
the more your bucks turn

00:17:29.381 --> 00:17:33.018
into really expensive dining.

00:17:33.251 --> 00:17:39.224
Nobody wants to be accessibility
that kind of expensive, I guess,

00:17:42.427 --> 00:17:46.430
and this is where WordPress
has its own set of challenges.

00:17:48.433 --> 00:17:53.337
As I already said, it powers
more than 40% of the entire web,

00:17:53.338 --> 00:17:55.940
which is incredible,
but that also makes

00:17:55.941 --> 00:17:59.878
it a prime target for hackers
and for compliance issues.

00:18:00.312 --> 00:18:05.984
One insecure plugin, just one,
can take down the entire site.

00:18:06.418 --> 00:18:07.952
Here's the thing:

00:18:07.953 --> 00:18:11.055
compliance can't be a plugin,
and accessibility

00:18:11.056 --> 00:18:13.090
can't be a plugin either.

00:18:13.658 --> 00:18:18.863
If you treat it like an add-on,
you're basically duct-taping risk

00:18:18.864 --> 00:18:23.735
management onto a system
that was never designed for it,

00:18:24.236 --> 00:18:27.004
and that approach
simply wouldn't hold up

00:18:27.005 --> 00:18:28.506
in regulated industries.

00:18:28.740 --> 00:18:30.441
That's why, also, more and more banks

00:18:30.442 --> 00:18:32.877
are moving away
from WordPress towards

00:18:32.878 --> 00:18:35.946
platforms where compliance
and accessibility

00:18:35.947 --> 00:18:38.216
governance are built
in from the start.

00:18:39.918 --> 00:18:44.221
Let's step into a real project
for a moment,

00:18:44.222 --> 00:18:50.028
and then see what I call
the WordPress accessibility pattern.

00:18:53.431 --> 00:18:56.767
Because what looks
so easy on slides often looks

00:18:56.768 --> 00:19:02.874
very different in real life,
it usually starts with design.

00:19:03.742 --> 00:19:08.045
Designers hand over their work,
gorgeous Figma mockups,

00:19:08.046 --> 00:19:10.514
perfect spacing, beautiful fonts.

00:19:10.515 --> 00:19:14.552
Everyone claps,
and then somebody says, "But wait,

00:19:14.553 --> 00:19:17.121
where are the focus states?"

00:19:17.122 --> 00:19:23.595
Designers just smile and go,
"Yes, we didn't design those."

00:19:23.829 --> 00:19:25.363
Next slide.

00:19:26.264 --> 00:19:28.533
Then comes feature development.

00:19:29.568 --> 00:19:34.572
Devs open Jira, deadline
was yesterday, so the job is clear.

00:19:34.573 --> 00:19:36.307
Make it look like the mockups,

00:19:36.308 --> 00:19:39.243
make it clickable, and then ship it.

00:19:39.244 --> 00:19:42.213
Accessibility tickets,
they are in the backlog,

00:19:42.214 --> 00:19:45.950
so the devs do what
we all do under pressure.

00:19:45.951 --> 00:19:47.818
They hard-code it until it works,

00:19:47.819 --> 00:19:50.222
and then they pray nobody
asks too many questions.

00:19:51.723 --> 00:19:56.894
After that, content creation,
so now comes the fun part.

00:19:56.895 --> 00:20:00.130
Somebody gets the job
to move 400 pages

00:20:00.131 --> 00:20:02.433
of old content into WordPress.

00:20:02.434 --> 00:20:04.902
Copy, paste, publish,

00:20:04.903 --> 00:20:07.504
and suddenly you get images
with no alt text,

00:20:07.505 --> 00:20:12.209
you have headings
jumping from H1 to H4, H6,

00:20:12.210 --> 00:20:13.744
and then 10 different links

00:20:13.745 --> 00:20:16.447
in the same page,
all saying, "Read more."

00:20:17.682 --> 00:20:21.852
The team says, "Just don't worry,
we'll clean that up later,"

00:20:21.853 --> 00:20:25.456
and you all know
what that means later.

00:20:25.457 --> 00:20:26.858
It means never.

00:20:29.361 --> 00:20:32.396
Then, only at the very end,

00:20:32.397 --> 00:20:36.367
the big moment, the site is ready,
the client is excited,

00:20:36.368 --> 00:20:38.002
people bring snacks and champagne,

00:20:38.003 --> 00:20:41.739
and everyone's exhausted but happy,
and then it always happens

00:20:41.740 --> 00:20:44.975
that someone asks, "Wait, did anyone

00:20:44.976 --> 00:20:46.912
actually check accessibility?"

00:20:47.979 --> 00:20:50.080
Then the project manager smiles

00:20:50.081 --> 00:20:55.152
and says, "Haha, yes, we'll handle
that later in phase 2," which,

00:20:55.153 --> 00:20:58.873
of course, is the code word for

00:20:59.343 --> 00:21:02.593
"This will never ever happen,"
and that's it.

00:21:02.594 --> 00:21:05.729
That's how so many WordPress

00:21:05.730 --> 00:21:09.400
projects end up live
with accessibility issues,

00:21:09.401 --> 00:21:13.771
not because anyone's evil,
just because real-life deadlines

00:21:13.772 --> 00:21:19.044
and "We'll fix that later"
somehow always wins.

00:21:22.514 --> 00:21:28.018
There are four major challenges
that I see again and again,

00:21:28.019 --> 00:21:32.823
and that's inconsistent
quality of themes and plugins.

00:21:32.824 --> 00:21:35.192
We have continuous content updates

00:21:35.193 --> 00:21:38.196
that quietly introduce new issues.

00:21:38.363 --> 00:21:42.466
We have unclear
ownership across teams,

00:21:42.467 --> 00:21:46.137
and the fact that content itself
needs to be understandable.

00:21:47.072 --> 00:21:50.675
Let's go through these one by one.

00:21:52.243 --> 00:21:56.246
Problem number 1: import bad code,
import barriers.

00:21:56.247 --> 00:22:00.218
This is where it usually starts
with themes and plugins.

00:22:02.354 --> 00:22:07.458
WordPress core and also the official
accessibility ready themes

00:22:07.459 --> 00:22:12.129
can be a quite solid foundation,
but once you step

00:22:12.130 --> 00:22:15.799
into the world of community
themes and third-party plugins,

00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:19.004
quality becomes quite unpredictable.

00:22:19.204 --> 00:22:21.523
Some are well-coded
with accessibility

00:22:21.524 --> 00:22:25.643
also in mind; many are not.

00:22:25.677 --> 00:22:30.614
When experts audited popular
WordPress themes, over 70%

00:22:30.615 --> 00:22:36.421
failed on basic accessibility
criteria out of the box.

00:22:38.323 --> 00:22:43.427
This means if you start
with a poorly coded theme,

00:22:43.428 --> 00:22:48.867
you inherit barriers from Day 1,
and I have seen it in practice.

00:22:49.200 --> 00:22:51.635
One example that really stuck with me

00:22:51.636 --> 00:22:53.637
was a beautiful image slider.

00:22:53.638 --> 00:22:58.743
It looked smooth,
it had animations, it had autoplay,

00:22:58.977 --> 00:23:02.479
but it was completely
unusable for anyone

00:23:02.480 --> 00:23:04.982
relying on a keyboard
or a screen reader.

00:23:04.983 --> 00:23:08.987
It just had no focus indicators,
no pause functionality,

00:23:10.422 --> 00:23:13.124
and yes, no meaningful labels.

00:23:14.826 --> 00:23:19.629
Here, you could see, for the users,

00:23:19.630 --> 00:23:23.267
the slider wasn't a feature;
it was simply a wall.

00:23:23.568 --> 00:23:25.769
For business behind that website,

00:23:25.770 --> 00:23:29.973
it was a compliant risk,
and that's what I mean

00:23:29.974 --> 00:23:34.679
when I say import bad code,
import accessibility problems.

00:23:37.182 --> 00:23:40.150
The second big challenge
comes after launch.

00:23:40.151 --> 00:23:42.787
That's called content churn.

00:23:44.823 --> 00:23:48.358
WordPress lives and breathes content.

00:23:48.359 --> 00:23:52.062
Editors update pages, upload images.

00:23:52.063 --> 00:23:56.433
They publish blog posts,
they add banners for a campaign,

00:23:56.434 --> 00:24:01.171
and every one of these small changes

00:24:01.172 --> 00:24:05.043
can introduce
new accessibility issues.

00:24:05.376 --> 00:24:08.059
None of these things feel
dramatic when they happen,

00:24:08.079 --> 00:24:11.616
but over the weeks,
as you can see in the diagram,

00:24:12.217 --> 00:24:17.555
weeks and months, they accumulate
into quite serious barriers.

00:24:20.558 --> 00:24:23.507
Studies have shown
that most accessibility issues

00:24:23.508 --> 00:24:26.363
on large sites
aren't coded at launch;

00:24:26.364 --> 00:24:30.934
they are introduced afterwards
through everyday content updates,

00:24:30.935 --> 00:24:36.173
and I can confirm
this in practice when we audit sites

00:24:36.174 --> 00:24:39.477
that were once delivered accessibly.

00:24:39.544 --> 00:24:41.512
The problems we find later

00:24:41.513 --> 00:24:45.850
usually come from content
and not from code.

00:24:47.352 --> 00:24:51.522
Yes, that's why accessibility
is never a one-time job;

00:24:51.890 --> 00:24:54.659
it's an ongoing process.

00:24:56.194 --> 00:25:01.966
We have the third issue,
and this is ownership.

00:25:02.133 --> 00:25:05.302
Who actually owns accessibility
in a WordPress project?

00:25:05.303 --> 00:25:10.007
Is it a designer, developer,
content team, legal?

00:25:10.008 --> 00:25:13.978
In most projects,
the answer is unclear.

00:25:14.345 --> 00:25:16.880
When responsibility is unclear,

00:25:16.881 --> 00:25:19.918
accessibility falls
through the cracks.

00:25:21.986 --> 00:25:24.955
Designers assume
developers will do it.

00:25:24.956 --> 00:25:28.592
Developers assume
content author will do it,

00:25:28.593 --> 00:25:32.408
and then content authors
assume compliance will check it,

00:25:32.818 --> 00:25:35.666
and in the end,
nobody really does it.

00:25:35.667 --> 00:25:39.971
The reality is that
accessibility is shared.

00:25:40.338 --> 00:25:44.141
If even one link
in this chain is weak,

00:25:44.142 --> 00:25:48.513
the result will not be accessible.

00:25:50.815 --> 00:25:54.586
Problem number 4
is actually my favorite one.

00:25:55.853 --> 00:25:58.822
The first point,
which often gets overlooked,

00:25:58.823 --> 00:26:03.360
is that accessibility is not just
about code and design;

00:26:03.361 --> 00:26:06.064
content itself must be accessible.

00:26:07.832 --> 00:26:10.401
That means it must be understandable.

00:26:12.804 --> 00:26:16.673
The standards actually say this.

00:26:16.674 --> 00:26:21.578
There are criteria in WCAG
that require content to be written

00:26:21.579 --> 00:26:24.781
at a lower secondary reading level

00:26:24.782 --> 00:26:27.986
or that unusual terms
must be explained.

00:26:28.486 --> 00:26:29.027
Why?

00:26:29.046 --> 00:26:31.922
Because language can be just as much

00:26:31.923 --> 00:26:36.226
of a barrier as a missing label,
and we all know this experience.

00:26:36.227 --> 00:26:42.333
Think of how financial websites
often use banking jargon.

00:26:42.400 --> 00:26:44.901
Think of terms like EZB license

00:26:44.902 --> 00:26:49.374
or SCA authentication,
or effective APR.

00:26:49.907 --> 00:26:52.843
If you don't live
in that world every day,

00:26:52.844 --> 00:26:55.712
those words don't mean
anything to you.

00:26:55.713 --> 00:26:58.548
For people with cognitive
impairments,

00:26:58.549 --> 00:26:59.883
for people who don't speak

00:26:59.884 --> 00:27:02.552
the language natively,
or simply for someone

00:27:02.553 --> 00:27:08.259
who is stressed or distracted,
jargon is a wall.

00:27:08.393 --> 00:27:14.431
In Germany, government websites
are even required to provide

00:27:14.432 --> 00:27:17.067
information in what's called
easy language,

00:27:17.068 --> 00:27:22.139
simple, plain German,
because standard bureaucratic

00:27:22.140 --> 00:27:24.609
language excludes many people,

00:27:26.344 --> 00:27:28.912
and this doesn't apply
only to government.

00:27:28.913 --> 00:27:31.381
If we want to reach our audience,

00:27:31.382 --> 00:27:34.052
our language must be open to them.

00:27:35.119 --> 00:27:36.920
There's a small story.

00:27:36.921 --> 00:27:41.459
There was a survey
about accessibility in 2025,

00:27:41.959 --> 00:27:43.727
and one participant

00:27:43.728 --> 00:27:47.531
criticized the survey
itself for being written

00:27:47.532 --> 00:27:50.133
in overly complicated language.

00:27:50.134 --> 00:27:53.470
They said the questions
were extremely complicated word.

00:27:54.272 --> 00:27:56.973
Imagine an accessibility survey

00:27:56.974 --> 00:27:59.409
that was inaccessible in its wording.

00:27:59.410 --> 00:28:01.912
That's the risk when we forget

00:28:01.913 --> 00:28:05.717
that language itself
is part of accessibility.

00:28:07.418 --> 00:28:09.753
That is why I believe accessibility

00:28:09.754 --> 00:28:15.093
in WordPress projects must move
from optional to strategic.

00:28:15.159 --> 00:28:18.228
It must be treated
like security or data

00:28:18.229 --> 00:28:21.365
protection as something
you cannot skip.

00:28:21.366 --> 00:28:24.716
If you want your product
to be safe and stable,

00:28:25.206 --> 00:28:27.872
and future-proof,
it cannot be skipped.

00:28:31.642 --> 00:28:36.880
I'm going to give you a way
of working that fits into real teams

00:28:36.881 --> 00:28:42.119
with real deadlines,
and it has three ideas.

00:28:42.120 --> 00:28:44.389
None of them is revolutionary.

00:28:44.922 --> 00:28:47.992
All of them
are very powerful together.

00:28:48.426 --> 00:28:51.129
I want to start with the first idea.

00:28:51.162 --> 00:28:55.032
The first idea is the supply chain.

00:28:55.233 --> 00:28:57.968
What is supply chain management?

00:28:57.969 --> 00:28:59.970
Well,

00:29:02.707 --> 00:29:04.674
think about your morning coffee.

00:29:04.675 --> 00:29:07.378
For that one cup to land

00:29:07.745 --> 00:29:10.814
on your desk,
a whole chain has to work.

00:29:10.815 --> 00:29:13.384
Beans are grown, harvested,

00:29:13.885 --> 00:29:17.254
roasted, shipped, ground, brewed,

00:29:17.255 --> 00:29:20.224
and then finally poured
into your mug.

00:29:21.926 --> 00:29:25.762
If any part of that chain breaks,
moldy beans,

00:29:25.763 --> 00:29:28.031
or you have a bad roasting,
dirty machine,

00:29:28.032 --> 00:29:29.699
that end product suffers,

00:29:29.700 --> 00:29:32.737
and you might not even want
to drink that coffee.

00:29:35.840 --> 00:29:38.041
WordPress has its own supply chain,

00:29:38.042 --> 00:29:44.048
and that's themes and plugins,
and these are our dependencies.

00:29:44.615 --> 00:29:47.284
In security,
we all know how it works.

00:29:47.285 --> 00:29:49.152
You check them
before you integrate them.

00:29:49.153 --> 00:29:51.288
You don't just trust random code

00:29:51.289 --> 00:29:54.491
from the internet,
but when it comes to accessibility,

00:29:54.492 --> 00:29:56.927
that discipline somehow disappears.

00:29:56.928 --> 00:30:01.431
We Google best slider, WordPress,

00:30:01.432 --> 00:30:05.101
pick the one that looks nicest,
and hope that it's fine;

00:30:05.102 --> 00:30:09.440
it's going to be fine,
but it's usually not.

00:30:09.574 --> 00:30:13.443
That's why I suggest a little,
one-minute gate

00:30:13.444 --> 00:30:17.514
at the door before you adopt
any theme or plugin.

00:30:17.515 --> 00:30:20.618
Spend 60 seconds with a keyboard.

00:30:26.524 --> 00:30:29.993
Can I tap through
all the interactive elements,

00:30:29.994 --> 00:30:32.763
and does the order make sense?

00:30:33.898 --> 00:30:38.769
Can I activate buttons
and links using enter or space?

00:30:39.504 --> 00:30:44.007
Can I close modals
or drop-downs with escape?

00:30:44.008 --> 00:30:47.777
Is the focus always
visible and clear?

00:30:47.778 --> 00:30:52.368
If it fails, if it fails
any of these, you don't import it

00:30:52.878 --> 00:30:57.889
or you fix it before
it even ever hits production,

00:30:59.123 --> 00:31:01.712
but that's supply
chain risk management

00:31:01.713 --> 00:31:03.827
for accessibility, and it takes

00:31:03.828 --> 00:31:06.364
less than brewing that cup of coffee.

00:31:07.465 --> 00:31:12.802
If you only take one thing from today
before installing a plugin,

00:31:12.803 --> 00:31:14.337
tap through it once.

00:31:14.338 --> 00:31:18.242
If you lose your focus,
your users will, too.

00:31:19.510 --> 00:31:22.212
The second idea
is to make accessibility

00:31:22.213 --> 00:31:25.749
binding in development,
the same way tests are binding.

00:31:26.017 --> 00:31:30.921
We already block merges
on failing unit tests.

00:31:30.922 --> 00:31:35.058
Do the same for
critical accessibility errors.

00:31:35.059 --> 00:31:37.827
There are tools, we have Axe-Core.

00:31:37.828 --> 00:31:40.997
We have PA11Y,
that you can run in your CI pipeline,

00:31:40.998 --> 00:31:43.500
and when a developer removes

00:31:43.501 --> 00:31:48.873
an accessible name from a button,
the CI says, "No,

00:31:50.474 --> 00:31:53.910
that's actually not a moral judgment.

00:31:53.911 --> 00:31:58.582
It's simply how we keep quality in,
how we always did."

00:31:58.583 --> 00:32:03.453
yes, automated tools
don't catch everything.

00:32:03.454 --> 00:32:06.356
They catch the easy stuff,
but they catch

00:32:06.357 --> 00:32:07.958
the easy stuff reliably.

00:32:07.959 --> 00:32:11.162
That's exactly
what we want a gate to do.

00:32:13.230 --> 00:32:18.469
The third idea is something
we call Defense in Depth.

00:32:18.569 --> 00:32:22.873
Because if accessibility
isn't everywhere, it ends up nowhere.

00:32:24.008 --> 00:32:28.412
It is about building
multi-layered protection,

00:32:28.879 --> 00:32:32.682
integrating accessibility
across every phase.

00:32:33.017 --> 00:32:36.753
In the concept phase, you define
the patterns that will be used,

00:32:36.754 --> 00:32:40.824
not just how they look,
but how they behave for keyboard

00:32:40.825 --> 00:32:43.027
and screen reader users.

00:32:45.896 --> 00:32:47.631
This is what Defense in Depth looks

00:32:47.632 --> 00:32:51.302
like in the concept and design phase.

00:32:52.470 --> 00:32:59.042
It starts with defining
accessible patterns,

00:32:59.043 --> 00:33:03.480
and that means deciding
early how components behave,

00:33:03.481 --> 00:33:05.383
not just how they look.

00:33:08.753 --> 00:33:13.658
It means, how does
the keyboard move through them?

00:33:13.924 --> 00:33:15.726
What does the screen reader announce,

00:33:16.894 --> 00:33:19.396
and then how does
interaction stay consistent

00:33:19.397 --> 00:33:21.032
across the whole site?

00:33:21.399 --> 00:33:24.367
This gives your product
a logical order

00:33:24.368 --> 00:33:28.538
and structure,
so users always know where they are,

00:33:28.539 --> 00:33:30.574
no matter how they navigate.

00:33:31.442 --> 00:33:34.912
The next layer is checking contrast.

00:33:35.613 --> 00:33:37.814
That's where you test
your brand palette

00:33:37.815 --> 00:33:39.816
on real backgrounds,
not just in Figma.

00:33:39.817 --> 00:33:43.121
You make sure text
is actually readable

00:33:43.161 --> 00:33:45.388
for people with low vision

00:33:45.389 --> 00:33:48.191
and that interactive
elements like buttons

00:33:48.192 --> 00:33:51.633
or links have enough
contrast to stand out,

00:33:52.652 --> 00:33:56.532
and then, finally,
purposeful focus states.

00:33:56.534 --> 00:34:00.226
This is where you design
the keyboard focus intentionally,

00:34:00.568 --> 00:34:02.606
not as an afterthought.

00:34:03.007 --> 00:34:07.077
You make active
elements visually clear,

00:34:07.078 --> 00:34:09.713
and you help keyboard users track

00:34:09.714 --> 00:34:12.616
where they are in the page
at any moment.

00:34:13.718 --> 00:34:19.023
When you combine
these three predictable patterns,

00:34:20.224 --> 00:34:24.194
solid contrast,
and visible focus, you build

00:34:24.195 --> 00:34:26.614
the foundation
for everything that follows

00:34:26.615 --> 00:34:29.733
in development or QA, or content.

00:34:29.734 --> 00:34:32.302
It's how you make accessibility part

00:34:32.303 --> 00:34:36.640
of the DNA and not an add-on later.

00:34:38.209 --> 00:34:41.911
Finally, let's talk about
content and editorial,

00:34:41.912 --> 00:34:44.547
because even the best design system

00:34:44.548 --> 00:34:49.519
can't save you if the content
team doesn't know how to use it.

00:34:49.520 --> 00:34:54.330
That's why a short
one-hour editor training

00:34:55.500 --> 00:34:58.696
can make a massive difference.

00:35:00.998 --> 00:35:04.768
In that hour,
you cover just three simple things.

00:35:04.769 --> 00:35:10.074
That's alt text, how to write clear,
descriptive text for images;

00:35:10.174 --> 00:35:12.408
headings, how to structure content

00:35:12.409 --> 00:35:16.409
logically with proper
hierarchy; and link text,

00:35:16.689 --> 00:35:23.587
how to make links meaningful
instead of just "Click here."

00:35:24.488 --> 00:35:27.824
It's not about turning editors
into accessibility experts;

00:35:27.825 --> 00:35:30.493
it's about giving them
the awareness to avoid

00:35:30.494 --> 00:35:36.300
breaking accessibility by accident.

00:35:38.402 --> 00:35:42.839
Then, inside Gutenberg,
you can integrate

00:35:42.840 --> 00:35:45.489
small accessibility checkers like

00:35:46.580 --> 00:35:51.289
a heading hierarchy
checker that warns

00:35:51.290 --> 00:35:55.386
when someone jumps
from an H2 straight to an H4.

00:35:56.787 --> 00:35:59.323
When you do this,

00:36:02.526 --> 00:36:04.861
when you train
your editors and give them

00:36:04.862 --> 00:36:08.732
the right tools,
three really good things happen.

00:36:08.966 --> 00:36:12.535
First, you make
the good way the easy way.

00:36:12.536 --> 00:36:15.538
Accessibility stops
feeling like extra work.

00:36:15.539 --> 00:36:18.142
It just becomes the normal workflow.

00:36:18.275 --> 00:36:20.984
Second, you reduce regressions

00:36:20.985 --> 00:36:24.080
because people stop
breaking things accidentally.

00:36:24.081 --> 00:36:28.285
They start catching small
issues before they snowball.

00:36:29.320 --> 00:36:33.790
Third, you create a culture
of accessibility awareness.

00:36:33.791 --> 00:36:37.527
It's not just one person
checking compliance anymore;

00:36:37.528 --> 00:36:42.131
it's everyone quietly
doing their part day by day.

00:36:42.333 --> 00:36:45.702
That's what long-term accessibility
really looks like.

00:36:45.703 --> 00:36:47.404
Because in the end,

00:36:48.572 --> 00:36:51.674
accessibility isn't just
code or design;

00:36:51.675 --> 00:36:54.677
it's human, and
the human factor in content

00:36:54.678 --> 00:36:59.650
creation is what makes accessibility
sustainable in the long run.

00:37:01.085 --> 00:37:06.257
There's one more ingredient
that makes all of this real,

00:37:06.757 --> 00:37:08.425
and that's ownership.

00:37:11.262 --> 00:37:14.932
Somebody has to connect all the dots,

00:37:15.299 --> 00:37:17.533
not to do all the work,
but to make sure

00:37:17.534 --> 00:37:19.903
the process actually runs end-to-end.

00:37:21.739 --> 00:37:25.875
In many teams, we call
that person the accessibility lead.

00:37:37.759 --> 00:37:38.578
Let me go.

00:37:38.579 --> 00:37:39.522
Okay.

00:37:40.758 --> 00:37:43.993
They start with pattern
accessibility, making sure

00:37:43.994 --> 00:37:48.031
that the patterns we design
actually work for everyone,

00:37:48.032 --> 00:37:50.334
both in UI and in the code.

00:37:51.101 --> 00:37:54.570
Then they oversee CI gate monitoring,

00:37:54.571 --> 00:37:57.607
ensuring that automated
accessibility tests

00:37:57.608 --> 00:38:00.543
are actually running
in the continuous

00:38:00.544 --> 00:38:04.247
integration pipeline,
and that they block merge

00:38:04.248 --> 00:38:05.282
when something breaks.

00:38:06.450 --> 00:38:09.185
Next comes QA process verification.

00:38:09.186 --> 00:38:12.822
They make sure
there's a real screen reader

00:38:12.823 --> 00:38:16.392
and also keyboard check during QA,

00:38:16.393 --> 00:38:21.764
not just "Looks fine
on Chrome. Perfect."

00:38:21.765 --> 00:38:25.703
Then there's the clear communication.

00:38:26.670 --> 00:38:28.439
They guide the team.

00:38:28.772 --> 00:38:31.474
They share learnings
and keep accessibility

00:38:31.475 --> 00:38:36.079
visible instead
of buried in Jira tickets,

00:38:36.080 --> 00:38:38.448
and finally, training.

00:38:38.449 --> 00:38:42.151
They are organizing short,
role-specific sessions

00:38:42.152 --> 00:38:44.020
so that designers, developers,

00:38:44.021 --> 00:38:48.759
and editors each understand
their part in the chain.

00:38:49.059 --> 00:38:53.096
This role doesn't mean doing
everything alone, like I said.

00:38:53.097 --> 00:38:56.967
It means protecting continuity,

00:38:57.501 --> 00:39:00.671
because if nobody owns accessibility,

00:39:01.005 --> 00:39:04.807
it becomes a beautiful idea
that slowly fades

00:39:04.808 --> 00:39:07.144
the moment a project ships.

00:39:07.878 --> 00:39:12.683
Yes, the accessibility
lead keeps it alive.

00:39:14.685 --> 00:39:17.220
We've talked about the risks.

00:39:17.221 --> 00:39:20.423
Now let's look
at how to make accessibility part

00:39:20.424 --> 00:39:21.692
of your daily workflow.

00:39:23.560 --> 00:39:25.461
Accessibility in WordPress

00:39:25.462 --> 00:39:28.664
doesn't have to be some big,
scary topic.

00:39:28.665 --> 00:39:32.069
At the end of a project,

00:39:35.839 --> 00:39:38.188
it's just another part
of building something

00:39:38.189 --> 00:39:40.143
that actually works for everyone.

